South Africa has signed a plan to support its steel industry, the Department of Trade, Industry and Competition said. The so-called Steel and Metal Fabrication Master Plan agreed by the government and stakeholders in the industry that contributes R600 billion ($43.7 billion) to gross domestic product “provides a blueprint for the industry to re-energise itself and expand production,” the department said Sunday in a statement posted on its website. Subscribe for full access to all our share and unit trust data tools, our award-winning articles, and support quality journalism in the process. You will be redirected to a checkout page.
